2. LOAD THE CALIFORNIA HOUSING DATASET¶

In [4]:
#The first row usually represents the column names so we can read them like this
column_names = np.loadtxt(open("data/california_housing_train.csv", "rb"), delimiter=",", max_rows=1, dtype = str) 

# We get the remaining rows as the data
data = np.loadtxt(open("data/california_housing_train.csv", "rb"), delimiter=",", skiprows=1, dtype = str) 

X = data[:,:-1].astype(np.float) # [ : , : -1] - all row values and all column values except last 
y = data[:,-1].astype(np.float)  # [ : , -1] - all row values and only last column values

N = X.shape[0]
number_of_features = X.shape[1]
feature_names = column_names[:-1]
feature_names = [feature_name.replace('\"', '') for feature_name in feature_names]

print(X.shape)
print(y.shape)
print(feature_names)

3.5 Between feature dependence - correlation¶

In [9]:
correlation_matrix = np.ones((number_of_features +1 ,number_of_features +1))
for i in range(number_of_features): 
    measure = X[:,i]
    for j in range(number_of_features):
        measure2 = X[:,j]
        corr, _ = stats.pearsonr(measure, measure2)
        correlation_matrix[i][j] = corr

for i in range(number_of_features): 
    measure = X[:,i]
    j = number_of_features
    measure2 = y
    corr, _ = stats.pearsonr(measure, measure2)
    correlation_matrix[i][j] = corr
    correlation_matrix[j][i] = corr

plt.figure()
plt.imshow(correlation_matrix, cmap = "inferno", vmin=-1, vmax=1) 
plt.colorbar()
plt.show()

6. FITTING AND EVALUATION OF MODELS¶

6.1 LINEAR REGRESSION MODEL¶

In [22]:
reg = LinearRegression().fit(X_train, y_train)
print("Coefficients W")
print(reg.coef_)
print("Intercept W0")
print(reg.intercept_ )
y_pred = reg.predict(X_test)
print("Error")
reg_meanSquaredError = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
print(reg_meanSquaredError)

plt.figure()
plt.plot(np.arange(len(reg.coef_)), reg.coef_, ".",  markersize=15, color = "darkgreen")
plt.xlabel("Feature number")
plt.ylabel("Coefficients w")
plt.title("Coefficient Weights")
plt.show()

7. Quadratic Basis Function Expansion of Data¶

7.1 Linear Regression Model with Quadratic Basis Function Expansion¶

In [36]:
reg2 = make_pipeline(PolynomialFeatures(2), LinearRegression())
reg2.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred = reg2.predict(X_test)
print("Total number of coefficients", len(reg2.named_steps['linearregression'].coef_))
print("Error of Regression with Quadratic Basis Function Expansion")
reg2_meanSquaredError = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
print(reg2_meanSquaredError)
print("Error of Regression without Quadratic Basis Function Expansion")
print(reg_meanSquaredError)

plt.figure()
plt.plot(np.arange(len(reg2.named_steps['linearregression'].coef_)), reg2.named_steps['linearregression'].coef_, ".",  markersize=15, color = "darkgreen")
plt.xlabel("Feature number")
plt.ylabel("Coefficients w")
plt.title("Coefficient Weights")
plt.show()

y_pred = ridge2.predict(X_test)
